observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that Management consider organizing and establishing a GSO to be headed by a permanent Department Head to take over the duties and responsibilities as provided under Section 490 of the Local Government Code due to the increasing number of assets owned by the LGU that needs to be accounted for.
We also recommended that Management:
Reconstitute the Inventory Committee that will take charge in the conduct of a thorough and complete physical inventory of the Municipality’s properties, thereafter, prepare the RPCPPE in the prescribed form as shown in Annex 49 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume II and submit the same to the Auditor not later than January 31 of each year;
Direct the Inventory Committee to determine and indicate in the RPCPPE the actual quantity on hand, physical condition and the accountable officer of each item of property;
Direct the GSO to assign a unique property number and specific property name for each PPE item for proper identification; and
Implement the “One-Time Cleansing of PPE accounts” as provided under COA Circular No. 2020-006 to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require:

The Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory of the local roads under the LGU’s jurisdiction and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Road Network System;

The designated General Service Officer to render a report on Local Road Network at the end of the accounting period, maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Cards for all roads and its components;

The Municipal Engineer to provide the OIC - Municipal Accountant the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

The OIC - Municipal Accountant to keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network and reconcile the same to the result of the physical inventory taking at the end of each year; and

The OIC - Municipal Accountant to include the necessary disclosure on the total road network system in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the designated GSO to facilitate the immediate disposal of the aforementioned unserviceable properties and waste materials to recoup any salvage value thereof.  

           Specifically, we reiterate the following measures:

Create an Appraisal and Disposal Committee, whose members are required to attend relevant trainings on property management, particularly on the disposal of unserviceable properties and waste materials, should they lack the necessary technical competence;

To conduct an appraisal of the unserviceable properties and waste materials and furnish the auditor a copy of the appraisal report thereof;

Dispose the unserviceable properties based on the most appropriate mode of disposal pursuant to the provisions of Sections 379 to 381 of RA No. 7160 and COA Circular Nos. 89-296 and 92-386 following the procedures shown in flow chart of the disposal of property (Annex 6);

The Appraisal Committee to fast track the appraisal of the cost of the demolished Municipal Hall Building and other improvements.

Further, we recommended that the LCE direct the Municipal Accountant to derecognize the costs of these properties once the disposal thereof has been completed.

We recommended that Management:

Adopt prescribed control procedures in the receipt, inventory and issuance of donations- in kind, and record the proper cost of the ending inventory based on the value declared by the donor, if available, or using the prevailing market price of the donated items in the books or in the registries, as applicable;

Require the concerned offices/units to properly categorize the Donations- in Kind received by the Municipality and intended for COVID-19 response and other calamities reported in the Summary/List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances for consolidation;

Require the MDRRMO to submit a consolidated report on Summary/List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances, separately for Cash and In-Kind transactions, to the NDRRMC through the OCD, copy furnished the Auditor, as required in COA Circular 2014-002 and 2020-009;

Require the OIC-GSO to maintain Registry of Donated Relief Goods for DRRM to properly account for the ending inventory balances; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements information pertaining to DRRM not evident on the face of the financial statements.

We reiterated our previous years’ recommendations that Management take the following immediate courses of actions:

Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) to record in the books all the unrecorded reconciling items as of December 31, 2019, including the reversal to Accounts Payable of the stale checks.  Henceforth, record immediately the reconciling items after preparation of the BRS;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to exert extra effort to locate the lacking documents in order that other reconciling items of ₱1.30 million may be cleared;

Direct the ICO-Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to submit and record in the books, respectively, the 46 unrecorded disbursement vouchers totaling ₱2.31 million and thereafter submit the same to the Auditor for audit to avoid suspensions or disallowances; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to analyze carefully the transactions before recording in the books to avoid erroneous charging of disbursements in the bank accounts.

